					<description><![CDATA[<img width="768" height="432" src="https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-768x432.png" class="attachment-medium_large size-medium_large wp-post-image" alt="MiCA Decoded: Why the Regulator Sees Your Compliance Team as a Single Brain" style="float:left; margin:0 15px 15px 0;" decoding="async" loading="lazy" srcset="https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-300x169.png 300w, https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-1024x576.png 1024w, https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-768x432.png 768w, https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-190x107.png 190w, https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-380x214.png 380w, https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk-760x428.png 760w, https://static.news.bitcoin.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/article-8-header_nwmk.png 1280w" sizes="auto, (max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px" />The organizational chart with the right job titles will not get you licensed. What the regulator is looking for is a compliance architecture: documented independence, collective expertise across three distinct knowledge domains, and real institutional substance. This is how that standard works in practice. MiCA Decoded is a 12-article weekly series for Bitcoin.com News, co-authored [&#8230;]]]></description>
		
		
		
